In short: JPA is a specification, Hibernate is the implementation, and Spring Data JPA is an abstraction layer.

The Analogy: The Restaurant
To understand the difference, imagine a modern restaurant:

JPA is the Menu/Guidelines: It defines what food options exist and standardizes how ordering should work. It is just text on paper.
Hibernate is the Chef: The chef is real and actually goes into the kitchen to chop vegetables, cook the meat, and make your food.
Spring Data JPA is the Waiter: Instead of you walking into the kitchen to talk directly to the chef, you tell the waiter, "Bring me a burger." The waiter takes care of translating your simple request to the chef.

Detailed Comparison
1. JPA (Jakarta Persistence API)
JPA is not a framework and it contains no code. It is a document containing a set of rules, interfaces, and specifications defined by Java.
It tells Java developers: "If you want to map a Java class to a database table, you must use annotations like @Entity, @Id, and @Table."
You cannot run JPA by itself because interfaces don't contain operational code.

2. Hibernate (The ORM Engine)
Hibernate is a concrete framework that actually does the work. It implements the rules laid out by JPA.
It reads your @Entity classes and generates real raw SQL scripts (SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) under the hood.
Before Spring Data JPA existed, developers used Hibernate directly by creating a SessionFactory and managing Session objects manually to handle data.

3. Spring Data JPA (The Layer of Magic)
Spring Data JPA is a module from the Spring Framework that sits directly on top of Hibernate. It simplifies data access even further.
When using Spring Data JPA, you don't even have to write Hibernate code or write queries for basic operations.
You just create a Java interface, extend JpaRepository<User, Long>, and Spring automatically implements everything for you behind the scenes.

